    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p>Formerly known as <i>Cardium turtoni</i> and as <i>Parvicardium turtoni.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_4285",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell small, almost perfectly circular, external surface strongly marked with 25â€“28 radiating ribs, each rib with a series of strong, sharp triangular teeth or tubercles (may be eroded in larger specimens and are rapidly worn away on dead shells, which may appear almost smooth).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_4286",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 15 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_4287",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to KwaZulu-Natal north coast.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_4288",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Small cockle found among shallow benthic sediments, or in sandy intertidal pools. Very little else known about biology.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_4289",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in, then filtering it through the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the ventral edge of the gill and then forward to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_4290",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_4291",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly distinctive external sculpture makes this small cockle easy to distinguish when in good condition, but the distinctive sharp external teeth wear off easily in older and beach-cast samples.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_4292",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 177 as <i>Parvicardium turtoni</i>).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_4293",
